\begin{center}
  \bf{
  { \Large Ciao distributions check list }
    \\[2ex]
  }
\end{center}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Look at
  \link{http://clip.dia.fi.upm.es/Local/ciao\_distributions/index.html}
  for instructions about how to compile Ciao and generate a
  distribution for every processor/OS.

\item Install the new distribution in the target machine:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Check that the \texttt{INSTALL} file exists and contains
    correct information.
  \item Follow the instructions in \texttt{INSTALL} file and check
    that every step works.
  \end{enumerate}

\item OS-specific basic accessibility tests:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Windows:
    \begin{itemize}
    \item From windows file explorer: check left-button menus
      \begin{enumerate}
      \item \texttt{.pl} files: load \texttt{foo.pl} into top-level
        shell and make executable (must generate \texttt{foo.bat} and
        \texttt{foo.cpx} files)
      \item \texttt{.bat} and \texttt{.cpx} generated files:
        double-click on them and check that foo program works
      \end{enumerate}
    \end{itemize}
  \item Linux/Un*x:
      \begin{enumerate}
      \item Check access to Ciao commands: \texttt{ciaosh},
        \texttt{ciaoc}...
      \item Check that the info file works well.  This can be done
        executing \texttt{info} and verifying that an info entry for
        Ciao has been placed, and also running \texttt{info ciao}.
      \item Execute \texttt{man ciao} to check that the man page has
        been configured successfully.
      \item Execute ciaosh and do something like the next:
        \begin{enumerate}
        \item \texttt{X is 1.0,X is 2.0.}.  It must fail.
        \item \texttt{X is 1..0}. It must generate Syntax error.
          Verify that the reported line that generated the error is
          ok.
        \end{enumerate}
      \item Run the tests.
      \end{enumerate}
  \item MacOSX:
      \begin{enumerate}
      \item Check access to Ciao commands: \texttt{ciaosh}, \texttt{ciaoc}...
      \end{enumerate}
  \end{itemize}

\item Emacs tests:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Visit \texttt{foo.pl} to check that buffer colouring works
  \item Check that menu options appear on top of Emacs window (In
    Linux Emacses, check that button bar also appears)
  \item C-c l to load the file into Ciao top-level and call main/0
    to check basic top-level functionality
  \item C-c tab to check Ciao info documentation also works
  \item C-h i to check Ciao info docs also appear in info top page. 
  \item C-c d to check debug mode in Ciao, and run foo:main in trace
    mode. 
  \item Move the cursor to last line of main/0, and do C-c S b to
    check breakpoints. Run foo:main again, and press 'l' to check that
    the execution stops at the correct program point. 
  \end{enumerate}

\item Running the tests:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Visit \texttt{settings.pl} to set OS and processor
    configuration.
  \item Compile and run the tests, and check that everything works.
  \end{enumerate}

  \begin{itemize}
  \item Windows:
    \begin{enumerate}
    \item Move to \texttt{WindowsSpecific} directory, and run
      \texttt{windows.pl}, to check specific characteristics of system
      library in windows
    \end{enumerate}
  \end{itemize}

\end{enumerate}
